@page "/"

<PageTitle>Prompt2Plot Demo</PageTitle>

<h1>Prompt2Plot Demo</h1>

<p>
	This demo shows how <strong>Prompt2Plot</strong> converts natural language prompts
	into SQL queries and automatically renders charts from the results.
</p>

<h4>Pages</h4>

<ul>
	<li>
		<strong>Welcome</strong> – this page explains how the demo works.
	</li>
	<li>
		<strong>Settings</strong> – choose which GPT executor to use.
	</li>
	<li>
		<strong>Plots</strong> – enter a prompt and generate a visualization.
	</li>
</ul>

<h4>How to use the demo</h4>

<ol>
	<li>
		Open the <strong>Settings</strong> page and choose an executor.
	</li>
	<li>
		You can use the built-in <strong>Fake GPT</strong> for quick testing,
		or configure <strong>OpenAI ChatGPT</strong> with your API key and model.
	</li>
	<li>
		Open the <strong>Plots</strong> page and enter a prompt describing a chart.
	</li>
	<li>
		Click <strong>Build Plot</strong> to generate the visualization.
	</li>
</ol>

<h4>Dataset</h4>

<p>
	The demo uses a public dataset collected from the
	<strong>ClickHouse GitHub repository</strong>.
	It utilizes an <a href="https://clickhouse.com/docs/getting-started/example-datasets/github">open dataset</a>.
	It contains the full history of commits and file changes in the project.
	Line changes are not included because of large table size.
</p>

<h4>Fake GPT behavior</h4>

<p>
	The Fake GPT executor does not call any external service.
	It simply checks the prompt text for certain keywords and returns
	predefined chart responses.
</p>

<p>
	Try prompts containing one of these keywords:
</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>bar</strong></li>
	<li><strong>line</strong></li>
	<li><strong>bubble</strong></li>
	<li><strong>pie</strong></li>
	<li><strong>table</strong></li>
</ul>

<h4>Example analysis prompts</h4>

<ul>
	<li>file extensions with the most modifications</li>
	<li>largest files with the fewest authors</li>
	<li>commits over time</li>
	<li>commits by weekday</li>
	<li>authors with the most diverse impact</li>
	<li>authors with the most commits</li>
	<li>table of favorite files for an author</li>
	<li>repository churn over time</li>
	<li>most consecutive commit days by author</li>
</ul>